				\begin{document}$${I}_{{A}^{0}}+{I}_{{A}^{-}}+{I}_{X}$$\end{document}, and the Eb and T are taken as 25 meV and 300 K, respectively. The γtr/γex and γX/γex values as obtained from the fitting are substituted here. Thus, the charge density ne is calculated from the exciton spectral weight using Eq. (13) and is shown in Fig. 8(d). For pristine 1L-MoS2, the charge density is ~ 5.5 × 1012 cm−2 owing to its unintentional n-doping attributes45. After WS2 QD doping, in the saturation region, the calculated electron density of the 1L-MoS2/WS2 QD HS increases to 20.5 × 1012 cm−2. It is important to note that the difference in the electron density before and after the formation of the HS is, Δne ~ 1.5 × 1013 cm−2, which is significant. This change in the electron density signifies the approximate density of doped electrons in 1L-MoS2. The inset in Fig. 8(d) shows the gradual increase in the charge density ne in the 1L-MoS2 with the increase in the WS2 QD concentration. Thus, these results demonstrate effective control of doping/electron density in 1L-MoS2 about one order of magnitude by the decoration of WS2 QDs. We believe that the electron density in the 2D materials can be effectively tuned by decorating with QDs of other 2D materials with high bandgap and thus, enable suitable control of the electrical and optical properties of the 2D materials, which is very significant for the ensuing applications.
